<subSubSection pageId="100" pageNumber="100" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="100.[93,620,1112,1759]" lastBlockId="100.[667,1193,213,830]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">
COMMENTS: In the original description, Hartert mentioned that Bürgers had collected 
<specimenCount box="[93,250,1351,1373]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" type="generic">17 specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hermann" baseAuthorityYear="1783" box="[300,527,1351,1374]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Epimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fastosus">
<emphasis box="[300,527,1351,1374]" italics="true" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">Epimachus fastosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the Schraderberg and that 
<bibRefCitation author="Stresemann" firstAuthor="Stresemann" page="34 - 35" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" pagination="1 - 96" refId="ref137564" refString="Stresemann, E. 1923. Dr. Burgers' ornithologische Ausbeute im Stromgebiet des Sepik. Archiv fur Naturgischichte 89 (7): 1 - 96." type="journal article" year="1923">Stresemann (1923: 34– 35)</bibRefCitation>
had reported on the collection. Hartert designated Bürgers’ adult male specimen no. 2094 as the 
<typeStatus box="[316,419,1470,1492]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[478,611,1471,1492]" italics="true" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">stresemanni</emphasis>
. Two specimens listed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stresemann" firstAuthor="Stresemann" page="34" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" pagination="1 - 96" refId="ref137564" refString="Stresemann, E. 1923. Dr. Burgers' ornithologische Ausbeute im Stromgebiet des Sepik. Archiv fur Naturgischichte 89 (7): 1 - 96." type="journal article" year="1923">Stresemann (1923: 34)</bibRefCitation>
have no Bürgers’ numbers given. These are probably the two specimens now in AMNH. According to Rothschild’s partial list of exchanges in the AMNH Department of Ornithology Archives, he received two specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[256,460,1677,1700]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Epimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atrata">
<emphasis box="[256,460,1677,1700]" italics="true" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">Epimachus atrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on exchange from ZMB on 
<date box="[276,491,1707,1729]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" value="1921-09-03">3 September 1921</date>
, and these were probably not available to Stresemann when his manuscript was readied for publication. The 
<typeStatus box="[824,937,243,264]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">paratypes</typeStatus>
are 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1005,1193,242,263]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">AMNH 677965</emphasis>
(Bürgers’ no. 1730), immature male, collected on the Schraderberg on 
<date box="[948,1103,302,323]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" value="1913-05-27">27 May 1913</date>
, as well as the 
<specimenCount box="[764,926,331,353]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" type="generic">15 specimens</specimenCount>
that were in ZMB. 
<bibRefCitation author="Steinheimer" box="[667,936,361,383]" firstAuthor="Steinheimer" page="15" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref137077" refString="Steinheimer, F. D. 2005. The type specimens of Paradisaeidae, Cnemophilidae and Ptilonorhynchidae (Aves) in the Museum fur Naturkunde of the Humboldt-University of Berlin. Zootaxa 1072: 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="2005">Steinheimer (2005: 15)</bibRefCitation>
found that there are now only 
<specimenCount box="[798,953,391,413]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" type="generic" typeStatus="paratypes">14 paratypes</specimenCount>
in ZMB, with the missing specimen apparently the immature male with Bürgers’ no. 2022.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="100.[667,1193,213,830]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">
The sex of the 
<typeStatus box="[891,994,481,502]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">paratype</typeStatus>
in AMNH had been recorded on the Rothschild Collection label as female, but an upside-down female symbol (= s) is used on the original label of both the adult male 
<typeStatus box="[961,1063,600,622]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">holotype</typeStatus>
and this 
<typeStatus box="[667,774,630,651]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">paratype</typeStatus>
. The AMNH number of the 
<typeStatus pageId="100" pageNumber="100">holotype</typeStatus>
was given incorrectly as 6777964 by 
<bibRefCitation author="Frith and Beehler" box="[667,1018,689,711]" firstAuthor="Frith" page="360" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" refId="ref123229" refString="Frith, C. B., and B. M. Beehler. 1998. The birds of paradise Paradisaeidae. Oxford: Oxford University Press, xxx + 613 pp, 15 pls, black-and-white illustrations, maps, sonograms." type="book" year="1998">Frith and Beehler (1998: 360)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="100.[667,1193,213,830]" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">
Long considered a poorly differentiated subspecies, 
<emphasis box="[817,951,750,771]" italics="true" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">stresemanni</emphasis>
was synonymized with 
<taxonomicName box="[729,799,779,800]" class="Aves" family="Paradisaeidae" genus="Epimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="atrata">
<emphasis box="[729,799,779,800]" italics="true" pageId="100" pageNumber="100">atrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cracraft" box="[848,1075,779,801]" firstAuthor="Cracraft" page="19" pageId="100" pageNumber="100" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref121493" refString="Cracraft, J. 1992. The species of the birds-ofparadise (Paradisaeidae): applying the phylogenetic species concept to a complex pattern of diversification. Cladistics 8: 1 - 43." type="journal article" year="1992">Cracraft (1992: 19)</bibRefCitation>
and later authors have agreed.
</paragraph>
